                        xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough">Bland</hi> MSS No. <hi
                           rend="strikethrough">327</hi></q>, with the name and number crossed out
                     and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">123</q> written aside.
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1814" notAfter="1828">
                        <p>Probably rebound in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                              >London</placeName> for former owner <persName type="standard"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/" key="person_44733962"
                              role="fmo ins" change="#role-assignment">Sir Gore Ouseley
                           </persName>.</p>
                        <p>British-made wove endpapers added to the beginning and end, then resewn,
                           abbreviated, on recessed five recessed cords, with three laced into
                           pasteboards. Edges trimmed then spattered in russet, with front-bead
                           decorative endbands of blue and white threads sewn at <locus from="Head"
                              to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>.
                           Covered in half calfskin <material>leather</material>, hollow-backed,
                           with five false bands on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine"
                           >spine</locus>, and boards faced with "shell"-patterned marbled paper. </p>
                        <decoNote type="binding"><locus from="Spine" to="Spine">Spine</locus> full
                           gilt, "run-up" back, with double fillets palleted on either side of the
                           bands, and zig-zag darts on top them. Spine panels bear floral scrollwork
                           and palemettes. Black goatskin skiver <material>leather</material> label
                           bears the titles:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">SHAH NAMEH<lb/> KHEMSEH I
                           NIZAMI</q></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>239</height>
                              <width>167</width>
                              <depth>78</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable condition, with
                           extensive abrasion to the exterior and board edges, bumped corners, and
                           cracked joints. Some endpapers appear torn out from the front of the
                           volume. Boxed.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="oval">
                        <p>Folio <locus from="701a" to="701a">701a</locus> bears a black oval seal
                           impression, intaglio-carved in one line of decorative combination of
                           angular and curvelinear naskh, bears the name of a former owner or
                           associate named <persName role="seal asn">‘Alī bin al-Ḥusayn</persName><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>14</height>
                              <width>17</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Possibly completed in the <origPlace cert="medium"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace> undated, but <origDate cert="medium"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1430" notAfter="1470">probably mid-15th c.
                        CE.</origDate>. </origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently owned or inspected by a person named <persName
                           role="seal asn">‘Alī bin al-Ḥusayn</persName> as per his seal impression
                        on folio <locus from="701a" to="701a">701a</locus>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Part of the collection of Persian manuscripts formed by <persName
                           type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/"
                           key="person_44733962" role="fmo ins" change="#role-assignment">Sir Gore
                           Ouseley (1770-1844)</persName>, who probably acquired the volume during
                        his tenure as British emissary to the Qajar court in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" from="1810" to="1814">1810 to 1814</date>, given
                        the replaced final folio on modern wove paper, consistent with other volumes
                        completed for Ouseley at that time (e.g. <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7313"><idno>Persian
                              MS 807</idno></ref> and <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7314">808</ref>),
                        then rebound in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                           key="place_7011781">London</placeName> after his return.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Apparently sold by Ouseley in the late 1820s to booksellers
                           <persName role="bsl" key="person_1555163159917201640001">Howell and
                           Stewart</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Probably sold by that firm to scholar <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName> for his
                        library at Randalls Park, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735" key="place_7011735"
                           >Leatherhead</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                           >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866-06">June, 1866</date>, paid in two
                        instalments of £450 and £400, and then moved to <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                           Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
